*Update: The question is about `t.Abort()` blocking, not interrupting, so this answer is hardly relevant :)* 

----

The documentation for [Thread.Abort Method](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.thread.abort?view=netframework-4.8) explicitly states that Abort may abort a static constructor. 

&gt; When a thread calls Abort on itself, the effect is similar to throwing an exception; the ThreadAbortException happens immediately, and the result is predictable. However, if one thread calls Abort on another thread, the abort interrupts whatever code is running. There is also a chance that a static constructor could be aborted. In rare cases, this might prevent instances of that class from being created in that application domain.

and 

&gt; For example, calling Thread.Abort may prevent static constructors from executing or prevent the release of unmanaged resources. 

----

While your example elegantly shows that a static constructor may not be interrupted, there is no guarantee for this behaviour.




----

# UPDATE

Here is an example where the static ctor is interrupted with Abort().

